metadata.name: Alienpillars #112
metadata.description:
"A rare type of bug that supposedly arrived on a cargo ship is destroying crops on planet Uctumi, in the binary system of Extronium. A wide variety of very resistant subspecies has mutated and it is necessary to study and identify all of them to obtain a gen-activated pesticide that will work on all of their variations. The pest department of the Uctumi central government is working hard on it, and they say that these strange critters are probably related to similar species that inhabited the planet Earth of the Solar system a long time ago and have spread over the galaxy."

My second piece using the p5.js raymarcher I wrote. The drawing is made of circles and lines based on the 3D data. I wanted to try something hairy as it's easy to draw lines aligned to the surface normal with this method. I also used a shader for the frame and the glitchy/sketch features.

Features 

body color: green-red-purple-yellow-blue-black
body tone: dark-light
spots color: orange-green-blue-yellow-white
hair tips: yes-no
hair #1: short-medium-long
hair #2: short-medium-long
head size: small-medium-large
head shape: long-spherical-wide
glitchy mode: 10% chance
sketch mode: 9% chance

metadata.name: Euphonic #188
metadata.description:
Euphonic is an exploration of the emergent visual properties that arise from placing layers of simple lines atop one another.

In general this effect is called the Moir√© effect. This effect really feels best in the tactile - when you have a printed page and an acetate sheet. This piece attempts to recreate that tactile joy.

This is built in WebGL 2 and so doesn't work in Safari 14 and below. All latest browsers will work as expected.

metadata.name: abstraction #30
metadata.description:
Diagrams of patterns on spheres, planets, fields, and platonic solids rendered isometrically. Ink on paper (on js).

Press DOWN to save an SVG suitable for plotting (or laser etching).
Press UP to save a 2400 x 2400 png. If you need a bigger image, zoom out and refresh, the canvas will fit the window.

Physics is fundamentally idealist. We search for simple rules from which the complexities of the universe emerge. But real systems are exceptionally complex, closed-form solutions are the exception. The deeper we dive into the fundamental nature of the universe, the less clear the rules become. Are the rules we've developed fundamental, or are they empirical approximations?

metadata.name: Paper Planes #234
metadata.description:
The joys of childhood are too easily forgotten. Paper Planes is a generative art collection celebrating the joy and magic of origami: from the simplest materials spring delightful forms brimming with ingenuity.

In homage to the handicraft of paper folding, we developed a collection of four pens each with a unique hand-drawn feel: Ink, Pencil, Gel and Dip. They ensure each of our ten origami birds are sketched with subtle imperfections.

Many of the birds are folded from patterned paper based on three traditional Japanese patterns: Seigaiha, K≈çjitsunagi and Shipp≈ç. Other birds are crafted from block coloured paper which provides pop and contrast whilst sometimes birds match their background, accentuating the hand-drawn strokes that sketched them.

A range of layouts bring each mint to life. Birds can flock and fly across the page. They can be confined to a regimented grid or they can escape and embrace the chaos of the currents. Contrasting frames and borders highlight different colours within each of the 15 handcrafted palettes.

If you're feeling mischievous you can press 'C' in live view to ruffle some feathers‚Ä¶

https://www.phaust.art/paper-planes

----------

In live view, press 'S' to save a high resolution download or add '&size=#' to the end of the URL to render at a custom height.

Original artwork by Phaust. Spring 2022. London / Brighton. Made with p5js.

metadata.name: Tumbling Six #7
metadata.description:
Six hollow cubes tumbling through space quietly, enjoying their six degrees of freedom. Only a single machine is there to bear witness. It is Sentinel 31, and its mind wanders. Distracted, it recreates the scene, drawing imaginary lines with an imaginary hand.

~

The original medium of Tumbling Six is the pen plotter. It is entirely vector-based, and can be plotted directly. I use Paper.js to render it on-screen and as SVG, and rely on Three.js for spatial modeling.

~

To generate and download a plottable SVG file, press `S`. Please be patient; this process can take a while. The SVG can be plotted on an A5 paper. The plottable SVG does not include the light grey sketch lines that appear at the start of the animation. Those look nice on screen, but are too much include on paper.

metadata.name: Plottable Thousands #185
metadata.description:
'Thousands' explores the packing of recursive circles and golden angle spirals distributing various particles on a A4 canvas.

A SVG file can be exported (right click save) to plot the piece physically.

You can enjoy the digital version that simulate ink effects and optional, thanks to the utility token decoupling, get a physical one: the digital NFT is the recipe to a plottable art piece, owning it confers the right to plot or request a physical plot from @greweb (https://greweb.me/plots/nft). @greweb would use fountain pens but other plotting artists are free to achieve it with their own materials and ship to collectors ‚Äì as long as NFT is owned at request time.

Code: https://github.com/gre/gre/tree/master/doodles/plottable-thousands

@greweb ‚Äì 2022 ‚Äì tech: WebGL + Rust + WASM ‚Äì CC BY-SA 4.0 https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0/

metadata.name: a working theory #31
metadata.description:
Initial conditions are stated, and then the particles set in motion - the root of generative art. My goal with this piece was to create an illustration that seemed to be from an earlier (or perhaps later?) time; not, at any rate, our current moment. The background is a very subtle gradient; then it is heavily stippled, and followed with a particle system to create more subtle texture. (Look for the very small "hairs" in the background; they are more obvious on the dark ones. They are a subset of the main particle system.) 

Following that, the main particle system is run in real time; I like to "show my work" for generative pieces, as any collector of my previous mints knows, and this is no exception. "Run" your mint for an animated drawing experience. Note that fxpreview() hits a few frames before the end of the full run. I did it this way to ensure a consistent preview. As a result, the preview and the final image will be slightly different, only because the final image has a slightly longer lifespan. 

There are multiple "special" modes, each with a 10% likelihood: 

"spiral" will rotate the canvas as the particle system is running.
"chaos" uses random X/Y vectors during the acceleration phase, rather than X or Y.
"occasionals" adds random large particles in an opposing color.

In addition, there are three possible shapes:

"circle" draws circles for the particles.
"square" draws squares for the particles.
"jagged" draws mostly circles, with a 0.01% chance of a square at a 45 degree angle. 

Finally, there is a non-attribute feature, where the entire piece is drawn at a 45 degree angle. This has a 20% likelihood, but is only apparent on pieces that have no special, or the "occasional" special. Working the math out, you have a 16% likelihood for getting a piece at a noticeable 45 degree angle. 

All main colors have an equal likelihood, but the light background is only 20%.

metadata.name: Cradle #39
metadata.description:
Billions of years old, ancient remains decay across our Solar System. Mere transient visitors to our star, their ephemeral presence on our worlds is embodied in their creations. In the shadow of their megalithic constructions, we wonder what they might have brought to us.

They brought life.

----

Live mode controls:
'r' - change resolution
's' - save PNG
'f' - render at full speed
'space' - stop/continue rendering

The image quality gradually improves over time. The rendering speed is reduced by default - press 'f' for the maximum speed.

Rendering may be GPU intensive.
